		<description><![CDATA[In a recent HuffPo article, Ryan Grim writes: &#8220;In arguing against the reading of Miranda rights to terrorism suspects&#8230; Joe Lieberman has a creative solution: Take away their citizenship.&#8221;
Some humans act as if we can somehow live in a state where there is perpetual light without dark. Changing the rules when faced with darkness in an [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>In a recent <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/05/04/faisal-shahzad-arrest-lie_n_562834.html" target="_blank">HuffPo article</a>, Ryan Grim writes: &#8220;In arguing against the reading of Miranda rights to terrorism suspects&#8230; Joe Lieberman has a creative solution: Take away their citizenship.&#8221;</p>
<p>Some humans act as if we can somehow live in a state where there is perpetual light without dark. Changing the rules when faced with darkness in an effort to stave off our feelings of mortality doesn&#8217;t at all change the eventual outcome: that we will, some day, meet our end.</p>
<p>Facing the darkness with bravery and maintaining one&#8217;s integrity, even when confronted with something as horrible as what Faisal Shahzad tried to do, is much more admirable than trying to switching the chess pieces around when you feel you&#8217;re losing, Lieberman. By trying to employ the old switcheroo, Lieberman shows he has no faith in our American system of justice.</p>
<p>To carry my point to an absurdist conclusion but one that may contain a whiff of truth based on Lieberman&#8217;s consistently bizarre political antics: It&#8217;s unfortunate that Lieberman doesn&#8217;t believe in America.</p>
<p>Frida Potente, I am Malan<br />
Be your true identity.<br />
<a href="http://www.iammalan.org" rel="nofollow">http://www.iammalan.org</a></p>
