		<item>
		<title>We’ve Arrived</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/ColorBlindPodshout/~3/sWH2Ab0EZ50/</link>
		<comments>http://iammalan.org/wordpress/?p=5#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Mon, 07 Dec 2009 22:28:42 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>contactthemalan@gmail.com (Frida Potente)</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Malan News]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[adulthood]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[choice]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[culture]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[identity]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[malan]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[race]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[race relations]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[racial unity]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[racism]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://iammalan.org/wordpress/?p=5</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[ Naturally, there was some trepidation on my part about creating a new race.
A few months ago, I approached a professor of sociology at a local university with the idea. Mainly, I was interested in her thoughts and feedback.  “That’s pretty far out there,” she said, and the expression on her face echoed her words.
I thought then [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div id="attachment_8" class="wp-caption alignright" style="width: 211px"><img class="size-full wp-image-8" title="Malans, One and All" src="http://iammalan.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009/12/diverse.jpg" alt="There's happiness in choosing your identity." width="201" height="296" /><p class="wp-caption-text">There&#39;s happiness in choosing your identity.</p></div>
<p><script src="http://digg.com/tools/diggthis.js" type="text/javascript"></script> Naturally, there was some trepidation on my part about creating a new race.</p>
<p>A few months ago, I approached a professor of sociology at a local university with the idea. Mainly, I was interested in her thoughts and feedback.  “That’s pretty far out there,” she said, and the expression on her face echoed her words.</p>
<p>I thought then as I do now: the idea was not as far out there as our long-standing attempts to classify people by somewhat arbitrary and superficial criteria. As people married those of different “races,” and/or found themselves growing up in lands far away from their place of birth, the idea that race could be quantified solely by one’s exterior appearance or place of birth–both things over which one has no control–began to take on a rather silly quality.</p>
<p>If a young woman is born of dark-skinned African parents, but grows up in Russia, and identifies with the culture of her adoptive country because it is all she knows, can she not simply be Russian?</p>
<p>Why does it upset others so if such a person chooses solely to be Russian? She might hear from her dark-skinned counterparts that she is a race traitor. She might hear from her adoptive comrades that she is not truly Russian. Why should either of those things be true?</p>
<p>It is interesting to note that, Africans whose ancestors hailed from Europe can be, quite simply, African. And certainly there is no denying the blonde-haired, blue-eyed Colombiana her Hispanic identity. There seems to be little quibble when the masses are presented with this cross-over. I accept the elegance of both the idea and practice of such cross-over, and the ease with which it is accepted. So much do I admire it, that I choose to borrow the concept for a larger purpose.</p>
<p>Let’s take a larger view: A young adult can choose from an infinite list of identity characteristics when moving into who they wish to be. Is it true that certain choices must be off-limits?</p>
<p>I can choose whether to be a criminal or not, whether to pursue art or business as a career, whether to volunteer or keep my time and money to myself, whether or not to have children. All of these things are part of one’s identity. Yet the race with which we identify, well, that’s off limits.</p>
<p>Silly, I say.</p>
<p>No more of that silliness.</p>
<p>I advocate choice in all areas of our lives. The choice to identify with a racial group not based on something as superficial as external appearance or where we happened to be at the time our mothers hit the 9-month gestation mark, but based, instead, on what and whom we most identify with. Based on values. Based on ideas and ideals we support.</p>
<p>These reasons and more are why I chose to be Malan. And why, you too, may choose to be Malan, as well.</p>
<p>Regards,</p>
<p><a href="http://IAmMalan.org">IAmMalan.org</a></p>]]></content:encoded>
